{
  "answer": "**No verse in the Falsafa corpus directly rebukes Ghalib or his motif of self-effacement (e.g., _fana_ as in \"Ishrat-e-qatra hai darya mein _fana_ ho jaana,\" where a drop finds bliss in dissolution into the river.[^1]) Iqbal's _Bang-e-Dara_ explores self-realization, human striving, and persistent love/sorrow over annihilation, but without naming Ghalib or targeting his style.**\n\nIqbal's closest thematic counterpoint appears in *\"Falsafa-e-Gham\"* (\"Philosophy of Sorrow\"), where he reframes love's trials: the beloved's departure does not mean _fana_ (\"Annihilation's art\"), as passion endures eternally in the soul rather than dissolving.[^2] Here, sorrow polishes and reveals the self, rather than emptying it—love \"lives within the soul as Sorrow, and is there to stay.\"[^3] Similarly, in *\"Insaan\"* (\"The Human Being\"), humanity is defined by restless power and striving for vastness, unlike passive nature.[^4]\n\n**Iqbal talks past Ghalib.** These poems engage Sufi _fana_ more broadly (persistence over erasure), but _khudi_ (selfhood)—central to Iqbal's rebuke of self-dissolution elsewhere—is absent from English translations here.[^5] No explicit dialogue exists in the corpus; Iqbal builds his affirmative self amid shared motifs of love, pain, and eternity, without confrontation.\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 86 (\"Ishrat-e-qatra hai darya mein fana ho jaana\"), [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/86-ishrat-e-qatra-hai-darya-mein-fana-ho-jaana/translation-2/#p-a9ff31).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 7 (\"Falsafa-e-Gham\"), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/07-falsafa-e-gham/translation/#p-e693fc).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 7 (\"Falsafa-e-Gham\"), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/07-falsafa-e-gham/translation/#p-e693fc).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 12 (\"Insaan\"), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/12-insaan/translation/#p-cb3c43).\n\n[^5]: Corpus searches for \"khudi,\" \"self,\" \"selfhood,\" etc., yield no English matches; _khud_ appears only in transliterations (e.g., self-display), not as doctrine.",
